## The Problem with Nested Callbacks

When you have multiple asynchronous operations that depend on each other, you end up nesting callbacks, leading to hard‑to‑read and maintain code.

```javascript
fs.readFile('a.txt', 'utf8', (err, dataA) => {
  if (err) handle(err);
  else {
    fs.readFile('b.txt', 'utf8', (err, dataB) => {
      if (err) handle(err);
      else {
        fs.writeFile('c.txt', dataA + dataB, (err) => {
          if (err) handle(err);
          else console.log('Done');
        });
      }
    });
  }
});
```

This triangular shape is called **callback hell**. It's hard to debug, error‑prone, and violates the DRY principle.
